4 HR____ MOURNING THE DEATH AND CELEBRATING THE LIFE OF CHERYL
5 SMILEY WILLIAMS.
6
7 WHEREAS, it is with deep sorrow that we note the
8 passing of Cheryl Smiley Williams on March 21, 2026, at the
9 age of 67; her loss leaves an enduring void in the lives of
10 her family, friends, and the community she so faithfully
11 served; and
12 WHEREAS, Cheryl Smiley Williams was born December 1,
13 1958, in Sweetwater, Alabama, to the union of Otis Nathaniel
14 Smiley and Emma Louise Moore Smiley; she was raised in the
15 Holiness Church, where she developed the faith and values
16 that guided her life and leadership; and
17 WHEREAS, she attended The University of Alabama,
18 earning a Bachelor of Science in Business and a Master of
19 Arts in Marketing; she later achieved certification as a
20 Government Procurement Counselor and Economic Developer
21 through the University of Oklahoma, credentials she used to
22 advance opportunity and economic growth; and
23 WHEREAS, for more than 40 years, Cheryl Williams
24 distinguished herself as a leader in business and public
25 service; she championed small and disadvantaged businesses
26 and served as Director of the University of South Alabama
27 Small Business Development Center from 1987 to 1996, where
28 she managed substantial budgets and launched innovative
Page 1

she managed substantial budgets and launched innovative
HR304 INTRODUCED
29 programs; she also served the federal government as Chief of
30 the Mobile District Corps of Engineers Small and
31 Disadvantaged Business Utilization Office, overseeing
32 procurement initiatives across seven states; and
33 WHEREAS, in 1994, she became owner and operator of
34 Spherion Staffing Services in Mobile, strengthening the
35 region's workforce and supporting both local enterprises and
36 Fortune 1000 companies; her office earned national
37 recognition, consistently ranking among Spherion's Top 100;
38 and
39 WHEREAS, Cheryl Williams was deeply committed to
40 mentorship and education; she served as a Marketing
41 Instructor at Alabama State University and as a facilitator
42 for Mobile Works and the Mobile County Commission; she
43 reached an even broader audience through her Business
44 Matters segment on WKRG TV-5; and
45 WHEREAS, her faith remained the foundation of her
46 life; she was a founding member of New Life Ministries
47 Church and was devoted to its ministry and growth; and
48 WHEREAS, known for her generosity and servant
49 leadership, she dedicated herself to strengthening her
50 community; she served as a National Board Member of
51 Volunteers of America, a member of Delta Sigma Theta
52 Sorority, Incorporated, and on the board of the Mobile
53 Chapter of the National Coalition of 100 Black Women; her
54 many contributions were recognized by her induction into the
55 City of Prichard Hall of Fame and her designation as a Steel
56 Magnolia by Mobile Bay Monthly; and
Page 2

Magnolia by Mobile Bay Monthly; and
HR304 INTRODUCED
57 WHEREAS, Cheryl met her devoted husband, Louis, in
58 childhood as neighbors; years later, they reunited and built
59 a marriage grounded in enduring love, shared history, and
60 deep devotion; and
61 WHEREAS, she was preceded in death by her parents and
62 is survived by her loving husband, Louis Williams;
63 stepdaughter, Leslie Doumbia (Lassine); grandchildren, Ibra,
64 Nandi, and Louis Charles; siblings, Otis Marlon Smiley
65 (Phyllis), Deacon Roderick Ladaraneal Smiley, and Shelia
66 Evans; and a host of extended family members and friends;
67 and
68 WHEREAS, while she will be deeply missed, her legacy
69 will live on in the many lives she touched; now therefore,
70 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE
71 LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, That the death of Cheryl Smiley
72 Williams is recorded with deep sadness, and this resolution
73 is offered in tribute to her life and with heartfelt
74 sympathy to her family and all who mourn her passing.
